iOS: don't define SWIGWORDSIZE64 on Apple platforms (int64_t is long long).

swigfaiss.swig maps int64_t to `long` when SWIGWORDSIZE64 is defined, else to
`long long`. faiss/python/CMakeLists.txt gates that flag on
`NOT ${CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME} MATCHES "Darwin"` — which correctly skips it on macOS
(where int64_t is `long long`), but mobile-forge cross-compiles with
CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME=iOS, which does NOT match "Darwin", so the flag gets defined
and SWIG generates `std::vector<long>` / `const long*` where faiss's real
`idx_t = int64_t` is `long long`. The SWIG wrapper then fails to compile with
errors like "vector<long long> cannot bind to vector<long>".

iOS (like macOS) is an Apple LP64 platform where <cstdint> defines int64_t as
`long long`, so it must NOT define SWIGWORDSIZE64. Switch the guard to CMake's
`APPLE` variable, which is true for macOS AND iOS. This is a no-op on Android /
Linux (there APPLE is false, so SWIGWORDSIZE64 stays defined — correct, since
their arm64/x86_64 int64_t is `long`).

--- a/faiss/python/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/faiss/python/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -23,7 +23,7 @@
     CPLUSPLUS ON
     USE_TARGET_INCLUDE_DIRECTORIES TRUE
   )
-  if(NOT ${CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME} MATCHES "Darwin" AND NOT WIN32)
+  if(NOT APPLE AND NOT WIN32)
     set_source_files_properties(${source} PROPERTIES
       SWIG_FLAGS -DSWIGWORDSIZE64
     )
